text:
these two. they are my forever medicine, my healing balm after a triggering week that reopened windows to a wounded past and reawakened traumatic residue made achingly raw again-begging to be held and felt once more. 
these two. they are proof of all that is possible on the other side of abuse and assault. all that is possible on the other side of surviving. proof that facing and feeling and braving through the hurt (in time) is healing and freeing. 
these two. they are proof of all that is possible on the other side of pain and shame and victim blaming.. of knowing & believing in yourself, perhaps for the first time. of loving and honoring yourself, perhaps for the first time. 
these two. they are proof of all that is possible once you reclaim your (trembling) voice and unleash the story that lays hidden beneath your tired bones, buried beneath the heavy weight of feigned “i’m fine” and “everything’s just great.” responses you learn to barely breathe out of that forced smile. 
these two. they are proof of all that is possible once you harness the courage to un-silence what’s been silenced and transform that pain of yours into power. and into purpose. and there is no greater purpose than to refuse to be unheard and unseen any longer, to fiercely and finally stand unapologetically naked in your pained & precious truth, and in turn allow that bravely bare naked truth of yours to lead you to not only love and family and wholeness and god, but to a tribe of all the others that have been hiding too.
you are not alone. i see you. i hear you. i believe you.  xoxo

#metoo #believewomen #believesurvivors #wewillnotstop 
#feelingishealing #love #family #traumarecovery #traumatodharma

text:
i have never been more disgusted with liberals, especially liberal feminists, more than i have now.
. 
here is my challenge to every single one of you regarding kavanaugh; prove it. if it cannot be proven, then he is innocent, or do we not believe in the constitution anymore? do we go simply by mob justice? is the court of public opinion now the way in which we govern ourselves? .
i’ve received messages from some i had respect for at one point; we’ve held discussions on various political topics, but to see you now stand with #believesurvivors is in direct opposition of the sixth amendment. the very same rights which helps prosecute rapists. .
this was never about justice. this was never about women’s rights. this was about smearing a trump pic for scotus by any means necessary. if all it takes nowadays to remove somebody from a job is just of the scent of a sexual assault allegation, then rip up the constitution because it’s clearly been ignored. .
feminism is truly cancer. it’s a foul movement of vindictive spiteful man hating women who use the term “empowered” as a club to destroy anyone they don’t agree with. privilege through using your sex will not help you. emotional irrationality vs logic shouldn’t even require thought as to which should be used in the decision making process. .
all this entire ordeal has shown is the disgusting tactics of the liberal left and how far back they’re willing to reach to ensure they get their own way. with each day passing, i despise feminist democrats all the more. you are becoming enemies of the constitution therefore, the enemy of america. .
every single liberal movement has been built on emotions and ignored statistical evidence that proved them wrong. 
#neveragain #blacklivesmatter #believesurvivors #metoo

text: i wasn’t quite sure what to do with my hands the week leading up to dr ford’s hearing. and i couldn’t pull myself together enough, to listen to her testimony live. it felt like the world had gone mad, and women were the only sane ones... and yet there we were, still left pinned under the weight of power and control. somehow, that day, i stumbled on this quote by a young poet taylor rhodes, “blessed be the woman who is both furious and magnificent.” and it resonated deeply. it fit me like favorite shoes, in this world where we are terrifying to some while still terrified of others, we are powerful and yet still remain overpowered. i was outraged all week, yes, furious. and still fucking magnificent. because that is to be a woman, right? facing the demons, then meeting the kids off the bus and helping with homework. these words became the prayer on my hands, a statement a prophecy a mantra i kept repeating as the hours of the kavanaugh hearing passed. and these words filled my head into that night. so i made this later, while listening to the hearing on podcasts and video, while watching her calm strength, yes terrified, but still fucking showing up. i listened through tears, furious and magnificent. i finished this block print yesterday and pulled my first test print, the same day a mailing address was shared for dr christine blasey ford. and i thought i’d mail it to her. because her strength and resilience is carved into it: the power of womankind. #believesurvivors #metoo

text:
juan miguel palacios’ “wounded” series portrays the current atmosphere of our socio-political world. the artist explains, “under the title "wounded", i make a reflection about these signs of violence in these situations of inequality, both politically, socially, and economically, during this complicated time in which we live. thus, in a clearly metaphoric way, i use the image of a woman who has been or is being attacked, as a symbol of the disadvantaged masses. if one has suffered the absolute injustice throughout centuries of humanity, it has been the feminine gender.” we hear you. we believe you! .

text: a força do feminino na luta é avassaladora como o encontro das águas. ontem foi um dia lindo e histórico. nós, mulheres, nas redes ou nas ruas com nossos corpos, ocupando e reiventando a política. marchamos contra o fascismo e em defesa de valores que a humanidade tem lutado há seculos para conquistar. não se pode em nome do que for, permitir espaço, nem mesmo uma fresta, para ideias e discursos de ódio. por isso que com garra e amor infinitos, lideramos essa resposta linda pelas ruas da cidade. um movimento de resistência que vai gerar muitos outros frutos para além do período das eleições. seja pela internet como foi no #metoo  onde mulheres pelo mundo afora compartilhavam seus relatos de episódios onde foram abusadas ou nas ruas em resposta aos abusos de um candidato, seja em nome de marielle e de tantas outras que tem suas vidas interrompidas. o recado é o seguinte: não vamos nos calar. 29/09 fica marcado como o dia em que mostramos para o mundo com quantas "fraquejadas" se faz uma revolução. e ela já começou. viva a primavera feminista!

text: blacking out my profile picture on #facebook today is a movement of solidarity with other women who want to participate & express our truths and stories to share by bringing attention and awareness to the presence, balance, full spectrum, and healing needed to address the wounds that our entire human culture is dealing with. withdrawing our participation from certain perpetual paradigms is possible, and we are changing systems of oppression as we reflect, take actions, and speak out. to me it’s a statement not about punishing men or disappearing, but one that is a call for attention to this dark matter of sexual assault, abuse, and oppressive patriachy that has been surfacing towards the light for countless centuries. as with all, it’s multidimensional in its facets & to be effective is absolutely interconnected to the resonance of its participants. every point of view and choice is a matter of perspective. blessings to all beings everywhere, and sweet healing balm to celebrate diversity and choice. this is an opportunity to contemplate a moment in time that is an action taken by some who feel called to this movement for even just one day on facebook. i support however you, of any gender, race, sexuality, faith, or nationality feel called to participate & hope u can feel supportive of other actions that represent alternatives. it’s all participation. end domestic violence! end sexual assault! women are powerful and needed, we deserve respect at all ages from family, friends, partners, lovers, neighbors, co-workers, government, legislators, and most definitely strangers. women are amazing, fierce, and are helping to heal our humanity and this planet. today, while my profile picture is a portrait of the infinite potential, time, space, depth, and regeneration of blackness i will be working on writing my #metoo stories to share..... i invite you to do the same~~~~ i love you friends & thank u for being warriors of strength and the stars of light that shine in the deepest darkest night! text:
posted it once already but it deleted my caption which took a while. 
_____________________________________________
this trial for kavanaugh v ford seems that it is going to affect nearly every group represented in the trial. upon being proven innocent: kavanaugh will have had his reputation ruined in the eyes of half the country; sexual assault victims will feel as though they have no chance in court because of the #believewomen and #metoo movement bringing allegations higher than evidence; the opposition of the democratic party will be seen as misogynists, sexists, and women-haters even further. if he were to be proven guilty: his reputation, again, would be ruined, rightfully so; all faith in the court will be lost as a single testimony would be proven to overpower a chorus of "that didnt happen"'s; abuse victims would still likely feel little chance as the battle ford went through was pitiful on both sides for their treatment of the prosecutor/defendant. this trial is messy, unsupported, and just sad that its made it so far. kavanaugh's actual stances that make him a bad nominee have been dwarfed under these false allegations and will likely be ignored up until his confirmation is done and gone.
_____________________________________________

text:
7 years ago i ran my first half marathon. a little less than a year before that...i had my own #metoo experience. it took me 8 months to tell a soul what happened or even admit it to myself. those days, weeks and months were the hardest and most destructive of my life. when i came out of the fog, ready to face life again, i started running. some days weren’t easy. i’d have to force myself out of bed but once on the pavement i’d tell myself “you can do this. one foot in front of the other. breathe. this is yours and yours only. he can’t take this away from you.” it was cathartic. painful even. but i worked my way back. one half marathon in houston. then another in dc. then phoenix, nyc, philly, palm springs, zion. every race week i would get anxious...feeling the weight of what happened on my shoulders. i’d tear up at the start line just thankful i made it that far. i’d put my headphones on, blare a mix of melancholy and drowning music, and i got through. each one gave me the chance to feel the strength in my legs, the power in my breath. with each one i got stronger and i healed. yesterday i ran the indianapolis women’s half marathon and in the days leading up to the race i watched dr. ford’s testimony, kavanaugh’s ranting, and the political commentary that followed. i was triggered, like so many others out there. the normal waves of emotions that come with race week came, but this time were more like a tsunami. i didn’t sleep for two days and got up on race day feeling defeated. as i lined up to the start line, the tears came stronger than usual, the weight on my shoulders was intense, like someone physically holding me down.  i put on my headphones, clenched onto my rbg pin and held tightly to my necklace from some of my closest female friends. i told myself “you can do this. one foot in front of the other. breathe. this is yours and yours only. they can’t take this away from you.” and you know what...they can’t. half marathon #8. 2:03:05. 9:24/mile.
#heal #breathe #onedayatatime #resist #ibelievesurvivors #stopkavanaugh #running #bi #halfmarathon #live #strength #training #vulnerability #power

text:
i’m a sensual creature.
always have been always will be, but i tried to deny that so many times in my life, fearing being taken the wrong way or attracting the wrong attention or god forbid something happen to me (again) and i be blamed because of my body and the way i carry it and the way i dress.
the fact is when i show up in my fullness and in my true nature, i’m a juicy voluptuous mermaid. i am flirty and fun, bouncy, bubbly, dripping with passion and playfulness. this is just who i am! 
i’m done with the story that says i need to hold back in order to be good, be loved, be accepted and safe.

i will no longer be afraid to be in this body, in all her sensual majesty. 
i’m committed to showing up all the way. 
a🌹💦
.
📷 by @bearosenblum 
#nolongerafraid #metoo #iamhere #sexyandsafe #sensuality #mermaids #waterpriestess #hereiam

text:
grande fratello vip, ivan cattaneo: ‘rifiutare una donna è peggio che violentarla’
mercoledì 26 settembre quasi mezzanotte, su mediaset extra va in onda la diretta h 24 del grande fratello vip. e’ notte, i reclusi chiacchierano, procede tutto bene nonostante quest’anno in pochi giorni siano riusciti a scandalizzare e divertire allo stesso tempo il pubblico dei social con discorsi un po’ inusuali come lo sbiancamento anale, a suscitare polemiche con le accuse di omofobia a enrico silvestrin e a porsi una questione morale sull’entrata nella casa di lory del santo dopo la morte del figlio loren. ma questa frase non è destinata ad essere facilmente dimenticata.

anche se non fossimo nei tempi del #metoo difficile giustificare l’affermazione del cantante ivan cattaneo: “rifiutare una donna è peggio che violentarla“. viene subito ripreso dagli altri concorrenti ma invece che migliorare la situazione la peggiora aggiungendo che “almeno, nello stupro, la donna si sente desiderata”. nel corso delle passate edizioni non sono mancate le frasi infelici o peggio e sono costate caro a chi le ha pronunciate. basti pensare al ‘friariello’ detto da clemente russo parlando di bosco o della frase pronunciata contro simona ventura parlando con bettarini intento a fare una lista di conquiste. mentre nella seconda edizione c’è stato il caso predolin squalificato per una bestemmia.

text:
(2/2) i ran out of the house and tried to catch my breath in the cold fall air and it’s a good thing i don’t know how to hot-wire a car, because i would have stolen my boyfriend’s car and driven until it was just me and the mountains and nobody around me for at least a hundred miles. ⁣
⁣
and because he is a good man, shortly after he followed me out and wrapped himself around me. he was worried about me because he is a good man and asked me for the tenth time that night if i wanted to leave, and i was still too proud to tell him what was going through my head. he told me earlier, before we walked into the party, that he thinks he loves me and i didn’t want him to realize just how fucked up and pathetic i am. so i said we could stay. i told him i was fine. i lied. ⁣
⁣
and eventually we left and i started crying in the car and i hated you. i am so angry with you and a god that probably doesn’t exist and the whole fucking universe for what you did. i didn’t deserve this. you did something so horrendous and unforgivable and fucking disgusting... and you can move on. one day you’ll forget what you did to me — maybe you already have — but i will never forget. maybe i’ll go a few months without panic attacks or even thinking about how you touched me without my consent, but one day i’ll be doing something innocuous and unsuspecting and without warning a hail storm will began pounding in my head and i’ll remember. i’ll remember how i trusted you, how much i loved you, how i told you i wanted to marry you and have your children and how much i meant it... and how you chose to betray that. you chose to betray us. you chose to betray our future. you chose to betray — and violate — me.⁣
⁣
#metoo

text:
the year was 2003 in january, just left bible college, living in columbus, oh.  i was 23 years old but extremely naive not versed in the nature of the dating scene.  we dated casually, he was older, played professional football, i was smitten and the second to the last time i saw him i said no at least a dozen times...our next meeting happened coincidentally at a gas station months later, he looked at me and chuckled with the most disgusting smirk and i said nothing.  i blamed myself for years, thought it was my fault, that i deserved it. 
in light of the recent year’s turn of events and bravery shown from women around the world i have found the courage to speak out.  i wish i knew back in 2003 what i know now.  i wish i could’ve been that hero to myself.  i'm encouraged to see that i'm not alone, however it breaks my heart that so many have similar stories, that women are not simply shown the consideration to be listened to and perhaps...just believe their story.  it’s never easy coming forward when victimized in what is sometimes the most traumatizing and embarrassing situations. assault, rape, and harassment of women should never be normalized in america or any country for that matter. 
#ibelieveher #cancelkavanaugh #metoo #believesurvivors #christineblaseyford #believewomen

text:
at 8am many women will be changing their profile photo to a black square, to represent a world with out women....but i don’t want to be in a world without women, and i’m not a black square. i want us to show the world what it’s like to live with us when we are strong, empowered, and ready to make change so our daughters don’t have to #metoo and bury secrets. 
i don’t want to be told i’m too loud, i talk too much, i don’t dress “like a lady”, my hair is too bright, i don’t “fit in” etc...because i love and celebrate all those things daily and have worked my ass off to get to this place of self acceptance. in a world constantly putting us down and telling who we should be, loving ourselves and being proud of who we are isn’t always easy, some days it’s damn near impossible. 
i am here to shine bright, this world needs my light and i’m not gonna dim it for anyone. 
love and support to all my sisters, participating in the “ blackout” or not, too loud or too quite, struggling or thriving. you are not alone, you are loved, your light is needed and you are here to shine.
i’m a #survivor ✊🏻 #selfie #pinup #lylablush  #rockabilly #iamwomanhearmeroar

text:
💁‍♀️a little about me💁‍♀️
-
my name is kayla. i'm 23 and live in southern wisconsin. i am a chemist, turtle lover, foodie, learning to eat intuitively, working on body positivity, sexual assault survivor, wannabe minimalist, audiobook listener, working to be debt free, zumba attendee, learning zero waste, and so much more.
-
i wanted to create this account to really show who i am. i used to run a semi-popular low carb instagram account but recently discovered that my strict low carb eating was causing my eating disorder tendencies. i am now following intuitive eating and want freedom from the diet world. hence my new account 😊.
-
since i stopped dieting i feel like i have more time and brain power to pursue other interests. i want this account to really showcase all the things i love and am working on. i don't want to be bound to a single type of instagram account. i'm really looking forward to getting to know and meeting all of you!
-
-
-

text:
my red lipstick 🔥💋💄
when i was young my mother taught me that good girls wear pink lipstick and whore’s...they wear redlipstick. i mean she never came out and actually said that....but that was the underlying message. good girls don’t, easy girls do.... insert a whole list of standards here. 
so i grew up avoiding red lipstick....not wanting to be labeled a whore. 
think about it for a minute....what is the list of shoulds and shouldnts that govern your life....we all have them.... what do you wear or avoid wearing....what do you eat or avoid eating....what do you do or avoid doing? 
who’s voice do you hear prescribing this list? 
is it a list you still want to live with?
is it time to wear the fucking red lipstick? 💄💋🔥
for me the answer is hell yesssss! 
ready to join me?

text_retweet:
repost from @resilientfatgoddess using @repostregramapp - how are you not being silent today? how are you letting go of the illusion that silence will protect you?
.
i do not care if it is only an hour. i do not care if you think i am disregarding some pact. this is not a time for silence.
.
it has actually never been a time for silence. yet, that is what the majority of white people do. stay silent in the face of the abuse, assault, and dehumanizing of  bipoc folx.
.
our silence and complicity is why what’s his face was elected. it’s why the other one was nominated to the supreme court. it’s why white women would rather take crumbs from men than use their voices and power. it’s why we (white people) have our own internalized misogyny we have to unpack and face.
.
so, we are having to look what our country is all about square in the eyes - because your silence has not protected you.
.
this is a collective issue that we must address and be willing to be uncomfortable with, wade through the mud, and see what’s on the other side.
.
there will always be more freedom in that than in staying locked in the silence.
.
.
.
.
#blackout #takeyourpowerback #whyididntreport #metoo #nomoresilence #resist #disrupt #nonbinary #enby #fatandfree #fatpositive #fatliberation #queer

text:
this halted me as i casually stroll through the feeds of posts.

it's sent chill through me, because the illustration doesn't need any words and it speaks loudly and profoundly.

that's if you been paying attention to what's going on in america, #metoo movements, suppressed abuse and trauma that's so many women live with secretly every single day of their lives.

you're clearly starting to witness the unveiling of ignorance, racism and  social disparities in america.

a lot people don't know what  post traumatic stress disorder, or 'ptsd' entails and the depth of abuse of any kind.

someone with ptsd often relives the traumatic event through nightmares and flashbacks, and may experience feelings of isolation, irritability, concentration difficulty, fears, inadequacies and guilt.

these symptoms are often severe and persistent enough to have a significant impact on the person's day-to-day life.

i know personally, but i simply don't talk about it, but it affects me in ways that i know and don't know.

hence a lot of people in america need to stop behaving like the trauma from abuse of any kind, know matter when it happens, childhood, in between or adulthood doesn't affect a person's life short, long term or primarily.

it's sad, shameful, foolish and ignorant to believe people's lives aren't affected by abuse of any form.

text:
i stand in solidarity with everyone who has been a victim to sexual assault, people who are told to be quiet, people who are courageous and brave enough to stand up, people who are going through a tough time, people who are scared of speaking out. i believe all of the survivors. and i hear you in the silence too. your voice is loud and clear. i know words are not enough to bring justice through the situations you have been through, but i hope it does reach you somehow with my music.

yours truly,
kailen (youtube.com/okailen)

#timesup #metoo #believesurvivors

side note: i wanted to dedicate this to afra as well for motivating me to film this. at first, it was just an instagram story and then, it bloomed into a full video. this is also for those who continue to give me kind encouragements. thank you for helping me break out of my shell to share my art.

"the idea that sex is merely a vehicle to be enjoyed by men and 'just something men do' had shaped my whole life. the myth that women would be sufficiently pleased by simple sexual interaction with men, on the most basic level, had been ingrained for over a decade. women as nothing more than bio sex toys is a concept so deeply built into the male psyche that i still sometimes have to actively remind myself that a woman’s value as a human is not determined my desire to have intercourse with her.
i am now in my mid-thirties, and i didn’t begin to think deeply about some of the disgusting things men do when it comes to not respecting women’s boundaries until about three or four years ago, and it’s connected with our lack of care for their sexual pleasure. the pushy way men harass and coerce women into sex, insisting and persisting until finally turning a 'no' or ’i don’t feel like it' into a begrudging or reluctant 'yes' is unacceptable." – chris saltmarch | read more at blackyouthproject.com 👩🏿‍💻👨🏿‍💻 //
.
.
.
.
.

text: i really wish this wasn’t happening in my country. i thought we were better than this. in the government of the united states of america, there’s only one group of life time jobs. that’s supreme court justices. it is their task to decide if the rest of government has gotten out of line ... if they’ve lost track of core principles and are treading on the peoples rights. trump has nominated kavanagh for this job. the hearings this week discussed whether or not kavanagh raped a woman in high school. on the one hand, high school was a long time ago. on the other, that sort of mindset doesn’t change. he was rude to the female senators questioning him. he acted like he was entitled to the job and outraged that anyone questioned him. sadly it’s all about politics. republicans have the votes. apparently it doesn’t matter if he’s a good candidate. vote this november. #vote #women #womeninbiz #womenempowerment #womens #womenempoweringwomen #womensupportingwomen #womenpower #womenentrepreneurs #womeninbusiness #womensmarch #girlpower #respect #metoo #metoomovement #saturdaynightlive #colinjost #michaelche #instaquotes #instaquotes #truth #think #true #liveauthentic #quotes #quote #quoteoftheday #vote2018 #vote2018midterms #votevotevote

text:
it has been a rough week.
if you’re a woman or man who has experienced sexual trauma, it has been a triggering time. 
please know you are not alone.

@rainn has said that they have been overwhelmed with calls for support. it feels like we just can’t do enough. 
here’s what i would like to do:
message me
text me
talk to me
or don’t talk
let’s just sit together in a safe space and be there for each other 
seriously, even if we have never met please inbox my instagram and i will give you my email or cell phone number (which ever is the most comfortable for you).
if you need to talk, rant, scream or cry, i’ll be there. asking absolutely nothing in return. no judgement. no opinions. just holding space for your pain. 
we will get through this together. 
#sexualassault #survivors #rapesurvivor #trauma #support #recovery #metoo #timesup #together #wewillheal #rainn #sexualtrauma

text_retweet:
#repost @coachlyndanguyen
・・・
your power lies in your ability to embrace both your light and your vulnerabilities. it’s been profound producing this book, it’s been incredibly emotional — each time i sit down to edit or reread the stories. you can’t not fall in love with people when you get closer and closer to the true song in their hearts... i’ve watched myself and my sisters show up and tell the truth this last year: in front of the camera (it wasn’t easy), walking our talk in life (and with each other), in the heart-opening (and heart-wrenching) essays we’ve written. this battle: are we too much!? are we not enough!? may we be free. what started out as a “book” is now my greatest daily practice “what is my fear having me hold back today!? whatever it is... i will lean in a little more. i will be exactly as i am, but i will love a little deeper.” ❤️🙏🏻 @coachlyndanguyen please join us on friday nov 16, 2018 in nyc. it’s for charity. it’s for freedom. ticket link in @freedomandfeminism bio. #losangeles #newyork #newyorkcity #manhattan #womensempowerment #freefem #divinefeminine #freefemproject #metoo #timesup #timesupnow #education #equality #loveisfree #unconditionallove #freedom #iamimmigrant #diversity #diversitymatters #representationmatters

text:
dorothy mary crowfoot hodgkin (12 may 1910 – 29 july 1994) was a british chemist who developed protein crystallography, for which she won the nobel prize in chemistry in 1964.
she advanced the technique of x-ray crystallography, a method used to determine the three-dimensional structures of crystals.
among her most influential discoveries are the confirmation of the structure of penicillin as previously surmised by edward abraham and ernst boris chain, and the structure of vitamin b12, for which she became the third woman to win the nobel prize in chemistry.
in 1969, after 35 years of work, hodgkin was able to decipher the structure of insulin.
she is regarded as one of the pioneer scientists in the field of x-ray crystallography studies of biomolecules, which became an essential tool in the field of structural biology.
in 1960, hodgkin was appointed the royal society's wolfson research professor, a position she held until 1970.
she was a fellow of wolfson college, oxford from 1977 to 1983.

text:
ok time to unpack a few things 🧐
.
.
obvs been feeling some intense emotions the last couple days. we all have.
here’s what i have to offer the discussion
.
.
.
what exactly is so frightening about hearing what women have to say? about recognizing that women are finally standing up for themselves on a wider scale? 
is it possible it’s just frightening to be held accountable for your actions?

most of my followers are men. it’s not missed on me why that is. but best believe i am going to use this platform to my advantage. i’m going to voice my opinions. maybe some dude somewhere will be like damn, i should listen to women.

i have many questions for men too. like why they treat the only creatures on earth able to create human life like total garbage. (cue not all men comments, can’t wait.) listening to, respecting, and treating women like actual humans doesn’t just benefit women. it benefits us all. how many genius ideas did women have that could’ve forwarded society but her boyfriend beat her to death so she couldn’t tell us? or she was just ignored at the office, they laughed her off? how many men struggle with not living up to the picture of masculinity forced upon them?

ok one final thought. this ones for the ladies. yo! it is easy to get frustrated and angry and feel helpless because trash like kavanaugh are still sliding by, trump is a sick joke, and even some women so far entrenched in these outdated gender roles are anti feminist. 
but we gotta remember how fuckin far we’ve come. this movement didn’t start with #metoo. it didn’t even start with the suffragists. it’s prob been brewing since the beginning of time, or at least the patriarchy. and we owe it to our sisters of the past and future to keep fighting! keep screaming! keep telling your stories. our voices have more power and reach than ever before. and how cool is it that this is at the forefront of discussion in america and the world today? this shit fires me up! they are starting to listen. the dinosaurs are dying out. future generations of girls are looking to us and seeing that they too can have a voice. and it will be heard. that my friends, is a beautiful thing. for everyone involved.

text:
the #metoo movement is triggering as fuck. i am hoping to god there are only a few things that feel more isolating than seeing this dark disgusting event spotlighted and becoming a hashtag. having to experience another part of myself that i try to push down being poked, prodded and focused on makes me feel so fucking uncomfortable in my skin. i would do anything to just slip out of this reality and into something a bit more comfortable ya know what i mean??
- speaking out against the woman that raped me literally changed my life. i had to live thru a reality where “always believe the survivor” was completely dismissed and debated upon. i had to live thru a reality where my gender, sexuality and character were also all on the table ready for debate and casual conversation. i had to move into a fresh new reality where the sparkly safe feeling of being around women and femmes was transformed into this terrifying labyrinth of confusion and danger 
i remember crawling into my bed after i had made it home and hysterically cry laughing for an hour thinking wow lol it’s been approximately 20 years since the first time i was raped and here i am at 25 being freshly traumatized by this evil i thought i knew so well. being raped by a white woman in the privacy of a home i grew too comfortable in at the peak of my roaring 20’s changed my life.
speaking out is one of the hardest things in the world to do. admitting to yourself what happened and verbalizing that shit is so fucking brave. it takes so much power and courage and energy; and the most fucked up part is that no one will recognize it. no one will care. people will ask so many questions that don’t matter. people will ignore it. people will fraternize with your abuser, pay them, feed them, love them, nurture them.
but the real tea is: it doesnt fucking matter
fuck everyone. you matter. you know your truth and what happened to you matters. 
the #metoomovement is just that; another pointless desensitization of a horrid reality so many of us have to live with and face everyday.

text:
who knew while i was away i'd learn so many new things about myself. 
1) sobriety is harder than it looks. especially when you're in a room of 200+ people at cocktail hour. 
2) you are stronger than you feel. waking up every morning feeling better than the day before is well worth the battle. 
3) the best therapy i've had, has been at the beach. listening to the waves crashing in and being in that water was the best natural medicine for my anxiety. 
4) i need florida in my life. is there a prescription for that?

text:
i tend to keep a lot of things to myself, and don’t typically join in to anything like today’s “black out”...mostly because there’s a lot that’s too personal to just share publicly. however, i’m so sincerely tired of the bad in this world appearing invincible. so many women and men that i have the privilege of knowing have been victims. i have been a victim. darkness only wins when we refuse to see the truth. so be the light. let everyone know you are there to hear their truth, comfort their hurts, and fight their demons with them. darkness only exists when we refuse to let the light shine through. 💙

text:
in response to the women's #blackout movement happening today:

in my opinion now is not the time to hide in darkness.  now is not the time to stand in silence. now is not the time to create barriers and isolate yourselves in an effort to prove that you are important and needed in this world.  we don't need more darkness and shadow in the world right now, we don't need our strong feminine leaders moving to the proverbial back of the bus for a day of solidarity.  what we need is light!  we need a consolidated and unified voice that bridges any gap of gender, race or age to speak loudly that the abuses that are happening and relegated to the shadows are not only  not ok, but will no longer be tolerated.  this requires that a bright light be shown to eradicate the dark shadows where these abuses hide.  this requires a stepping forward, not back.  this requires a use of our voices to heal and bring together not blame and create divisions.

i am taking a stand for the light in the face of #metoo and the #blackout.  i respect and honor those who have suffered at the hands or words of another.  i stand with you in your mission to bring awareness to the abuses that have and continue to occur.  i choose, however, to be a beacon of light instead of another unseen raised hand in the dark.  i choose to represent and stand for what brings healing, what brings love, what brings us together instead of fighting to stay in the hurt and divisiveness.

know that by me choosing to #lightup instead of #blackout i am not opposing the movement, i am offering a safe space.  a space where the darkness and shadows can be brought to light. a space where healing can be embraced as opposed to retribution inflicted. a space where a community can gather in love for the purpose of overcoming the fear that causes hate and abuse.

i choose love over fear.  i choose to be a beacon of light in the darkness.  i choose to #lightup the world around me!

text: content: sexual assault, rape // i know there’s been another wave of #ibelieveyou and #metoo discussions that have resulted in more disclosures of sexual assault. i want to say that first of all, i genuinely believe you and trust your experience. and second, be careful how you choose to disclose (if that’s what you want). there’s very little info or narrative around life after disclosing survivorship. yes, there may be a lot of online support for your disclosure, but in-person support may be scarce. there’s no welcoming to survivorship. people may try to hold space for you but not know how. it can be terrifying to be that vulnerable and not have the social & psychological support to handle re-opened wounds. i’m not discouraging people to disclose, rather please have a few people who can hold you through the process. your survivorship is precious and as much as this current survivor movement is asking us to come out as abuse survivors, your long-term well-being is much more important. you can disclose to your best friend, to a local support group, to anonymous crisis counselors on the phone or through website messaging. there’s a myriad of ways to be involved while protecting yourself from more harm & victim blaming. i hope you find sustainable safety & healing.

text:
“i just don’t think his life should be ruined because of one mistake” is a sentence i have heard a lot when is comes to sexual assault/abuse cases. it’s also a sentence that i think perfectly sums up the massive problem in our society. even though his “mistake” has ruined her life, his life should remain unaffected. it’s him over her. every. single. time. 
#timesup #metoo #overit

text:
consent part 5...
the media has played a huge part in the prevailing rape culture that permeates our society and ultimately helps to develop and nurture the problematic, and sometimes criminal, behavior exhibited by our young people and follows them into adulthood. everything from music, television, movies and social media perpetuate a gross negligence in how we should be engaging one another. the concepts of consent, permission and agreement are replaced with an attitude of entitlement that revels in immediate self gratification regardless of how it harms the person being targeted. our leaders are heard on the world news broadcast saying things like " grab em by the p*ssy"; music lyrics speak of young women being forced to engage in sexual behavior if a guy simply pays for her drink, and movies glorify toxic male masculinity. this constant diet of problematic and criminal behavior that trivializes as well as glorifies sexual assault spits in the face of decency where consent is the order of the day and the prevailing concept that is driven home for our children to adhere to. as parents, we have to be the greater voices in our children's ears combating these toxic messages. we must see the sense of urgency in having conversations with our children about consent early and often so they don't lack self control and develop an appetite for dominance and sexual assault.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
"all the women in me are tired." -nayyirah waheed.

the woman who is shamed for her fierce independence and success is tired. 
the woman who loves to receive affection, but is called too needy is tired.
the woman who is called a bitch for standing up for herself is tired.
the woman who practices endless patience and gentleness, yet called "a doormat" is tired.
the woman who has been told her brilliant fire and sexuality is wrong is tired.
the woman labeled a prude for being modest is tired.
the woman who was taught her only value came from her beauty is tired.
the little girl, the wild child, who is scolded for being "too much" is tired.
the woman who is classy and sophisticated, but seen as "stuck up" is tired.
the woman who loves men but has been traumatized by men is tired.
the woman who needs sisterhood in her life, but has been so damaged by other women is tired.
the woman who would give it all for her partner for nothing in return is tired.
the woman who is single and facing the world on her own is tired.
the woman who still has hope for her country is tired.
the woman who longs for a tribe by her side is tired.
the woman who is her own hero is tired.

but let me tell you something about these women. something that you might not fully realized. when we get tired, we don't stay down forever. we won't stay collapsed or defeated forever. wjennwe are tired, we get fed up. we rise again with the whole damn fire. hell hath no fury like a woman scorned. just you wait.

text:
as we come to the final day of international deaf awareness week i wanted to share this thought. not to shame other people, but to explain a position i have. on facebook many people are choosing to black out their photos in a day without woman protest. which i completely support. 
i am deaf and diabaled and have been for most of my life. which has contributed to me suffering multiple of these forms of violence. including my rape at 6.5 years old. something i essentially stayed silent about for almost forty years. effectively burying feelings, emotions, and even a significant portion of myself for almost 40 whole years. my facebook photo is the deaf pride bear. which signifies my signifies a huge portion of my oppression in life and probably helped. increase the likelyhood of my rape occurring. i will represented women, but my representation has to be intersectional. the deaf pride bear is also the international symbol for. disabled children. another group intersectional group at very high risk.

so having been silent for so long personally and having the disabled community silenced in general until fairly recently i damn well am not going to black myself out and pout in a corner for the convenience of men, able bodied, hearing, or any priveleged people. i am going to make myself such a huge, load, showy person rapist will throw themself in jail just to shut me up. i have no plans of being the cliché battered woman. that is why i am not participating in the blackout.

#solidaritywithmysisters #metoo #myrwordisresillient #iwillnotbedeafeated #iwillnotfadetoblack #intersectionalorbust #emmagoldmanorbust #closedlegsooenmouths ❤️👍🏽

text:
after a summer of scheming, femaissance is back with our first-ever 100% independent show, "proserpina," opening to the public on saturday, october 6. for the past month, our tireless fundraising efforts have been met with enormous success and support — and there's nothing we'd rather do than celebrate our success with you.⁣
⁣
743 camp street / 8 - 11 pm⁣
⁣
free and open to the public⁣
⁣
♀ music by @_dj_jess ♀ free drinks provided by @brewed_and_distilled ⁣
⁣
come out left of some steam on the dance floor, drink on our dime, connect with local feminists, and maybe even invest in a new piece of art. we cannot wait to see you.⁣
⁣
—⁣
⁣
“proserpina" refers to the roman goddess who persisted despite being abducted, raped and forced into marriage. this exhibition is our emblem of independence and a safe space for healing, celebrating the resilience of women despite repeated challenges and oppression. proserpina coincides with the one-year anniversary of #metoo, a senate hearing on sexual assault allegations against a supreme court nominee, and the run up to the midterm elections.⁣ “gaze” by @rachelloyacono_art. #artforartssake

text:
appel à témoins
pour mon roman de non-fiction survivor, j'en appelle à vos témoognages car je vous sais nombreux.
dans ce roman sera raconter ma propre histoire, je ne changerai que les noms. il sera accompagné d'd'autres témoignages, les votres.
tous les témoignages anonymes ou non, d'hommes, de femmes, qu'il s'agissent d'histoires anciennes ou de traumatismes récents, que ce soit une agression ou que vous vous soyez forcé, qu'il s'agisse de votre conjoint, d'un inconnu, d'un ami ou d'un membre de la famille... qui que vous soyez et quoi que vous ayez vécu, même si cela vous paraît dérisoire, si vous en souffrez c'est que vous avez de quoi. il n'y aura aucun jugement porté sur votre histoire ou sur vous, rien pour moi n'est "anodin", "pas grave"ou "à oublier" comme on a pu vois le dire... au contraire. 
témoigner vous permettra de faire bouger les choses.. mais avant tout de vous libérer, de faire le premier pas vers la guérison ou bien de vous prouver que vous avez réussi, que vous vous en êtes sortis.
car vous êtes quelqu'un de fort, car vous êtes vivant, car vous pouvez être fier d'être parmi nous aujourd'hui.
merci, vois pouvez envoyer vos témoignages en mp ou par mail : angelinecamus.auteur@gmail.com
nous discuterons de la façon dont votre témoignage apparaîtra, vous avez le contrôle.
je compte sur vous.

text:
what is stopping you from fully embracing change? what issues from the past may be holding you back?🔮🕸️
⬇️⬇️⬇️⬇️⬇️⬇️⬇️ for me, i've been being confronted with things that i never dealt with from the past recently and i can see how they've really held me back because i never wanted to deal with them. but in order to heal you have to confront the painful memories to move forward. you can't run away from them, you can't hide, and you certainly can't try to change yourself in order to protect yourself from that pain...i just never wanted to confront it. but now, i need to. these issues have stolen my sense of self, my self confidence, and left me lost and confused on pretty much everything about my identity. it was never my fault.

text_retweet:
“i’m willing to take the risk to get it wrong, so we can get it right.” mark groves 
mark, so well put - having the conversation and/or being open to it is a massive first step for so many regardless of where they sit currently in this whole conversation - how much i have learned and grown in the past year due to being able to hear all perspectives both men and women - affected or not - understanding or not... oddly grateful for this.  thankyou as always @createthelove 
#repost @createthelove with @get_repost
・・・
i’m sorry that i haven’t shown up fully to the topic of #metoo and what’s going on in our world. i’ve shared in my stories and commented on other people’s feeds, but my main feed has been free of taking a stand or position... so, first off, i apologize. i’ve been afraid to say the wrong thing and maybe not be liked... how arrogant and privileged is that?! survivors are silent because they fear people may not believe them - and so many other very real reasons... and i recognize, acknowledge, and apologize for my bullshit privileged reason.
•
i’m here now, and i’m ready to fully step into this conversation. us men are a large part of the problem, and we are a very important part of the solution. thank you to all of you of wrote me and gave me this feedback that has me writing this and doing this video. i love that i’m safe here to get it wrong, so i can learn how to get it right. i’m humbled and open and curious. and to all of you who have demonstrated such bravery in sharing your story (and to all of you who are holding yours private), i’m inspired and i stand by you. no more fucking playing small. i’m roaring with you.
•
i will never be able to understand what it’s like to be a survivor and/or a woman, but i will do my best. i invite the men reading this and seeing this to stand up with me. #createthelove

text:
#bt2018reviews
assassination nation
written & directed by sam levinson
***spoiler free*** .

if you took kids, mean girls, and spring breakers and threw them in a blender you could come close to recreating the insanity and beauty of assassination nation. with everything you see in the news of the #metoo movement, the feminism, the men hatred, the accusations that lead to ruined lives on both ends, the invasion of privacy and data hacks...assassination nation is incredibly relevant. sam levinson gave such a bold, unique style to this film. the dialogue, the commentary, the conversations, the editing, the humor, the cinematography. i’m not one to use this word but the whole experience was hypnotizing. i loved every single second of it. it starts out based in realism of a data hack of the students and people of salem (which the town infamous for its witch trials being the setting for this film isn’t by accident) , which sends the town into chaos. peoples lives spiraling out of control. it accurately portrays the mob mentality and their magnificent ability to scream loudly, point fingers, condemn, and jump to extremes. jumping to extremes is what this film does. it starts out based in a real world and throughout symbolically goes to extremes and goes batshit insane by the end. odessa young was amazing. her character has two debates at a family dinner table and at school with an authority, that need to be seen by america. people will be offended by this movie. shocked and disgusted. turned off and many will probably hate it....but i was in awe from beginning to end.
assassination nation gets an: a+

@regran_ed from @kidd.bell -  i can’t imagine what this must be like for women of color. the assaults of white women are always the focal point of the #metoo movement. she is blonde, white, slim, and pretty. she is everything they want and they are still dancing on her trauma. what chance does anyone else stand?
.
the only chance we have is calling, and even if we do that, and even if the investigation proves him guilty (which is a big if), even if all that happens, someone will be confirmed. that person will still be trump’s pick, that person will still be anti-choice, that person will still be a raging misogynist, because trump surrounds himself with people just as hateful as he is. i know this sounds bleak, but no matter what happens with scotus, we are setting a precedent.
.
** @sallykohn this only stops if we make it stop.  call your senators.  then call them again. 202-224-3121.  tell them to vote no on kavanaugh’s nomination.  then call anyone and everyone you know, especially if they live in these states — and tell them to call  lisa murkowski (alaska) and susan collins (maine) as well as jeff flake (arizona) and bob corker (tennessee). also call joe donnelly (indiana), heidi heitkamp (north dakota) and joe manchin (west virginia) — who are democrats in red states and need to be reminded of the right thing to do. ** 202-224-3121 ** #stopkavanaugh #delaythevote #cancelkavanaugh ✊🏻✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿👇👇👇👇👇👇👇👇👇👇👇👇

text:
yep i was one of the women who had old trauma memories of sexual assault ignited this past week. while not as painful & violating as my other fellow women have endured, i still felt the tinge of shame and old patterns that kept me from asserting and speaking out...and guilt of what perhaps they may have done to other women after me. i felt massive compassion for dr. ford and the affect this level of assault has on her life and felt grateful for this movement! 
i'm hopeful that this courage, this vulnerability -- will light up and #empowerwomen in ways we can only dream of. to say "no" louder and to speak up fearlessly. the two things i did not do at age 16 & 19. and that the men who would do such a thing to require either, feel this shift within us and be changed.

text:
today many women will be changing their profile photo to a black square, to represent a world with out women....but i don’t want to be in a world without women, and i’m not a black square. i want us to show the world what it’s like to live with us when we are strong, empowered, and ready to make change so our daughters don’t have to #metoo and bury secrets. 
i don’t want to be told i’m too loud, i talk too much, i don’t dress “like a lady”, my hair is too bright or too short, i don’t “fit in” etc...because i love and celebrate all those things daily and have worked my ass off to get to this place of self acceptance. in a world constantly putting us down and telling who we should be, loving ourselves and being proud of who we are isn’t always easy, some days it’s damn near impossible. 
i am here to shine bright, this world needs my light and i’m not gonna dim it for anyone. 
i give my love and support to all my sisters, participating in the “ blackout” or not, too loud or too quiet, struggling or thriving. you are not alone, you are loved, your light is needed and you are here to shine. 😘

text:
"20 minutes of action," "he was just being a kid," "boys will be boys," "this will ruin his life." there are many people that will try to diminish your survivor story. one of the ways they might try to do this is by removing you, your human person, from the narrative of your story in their sentences. but you, dear survivor, are worth more than that. your story is your own, and they cannot kick you out of it just because you make them uncomfortable.

#metoo #istandwithsurvivors #christendomtoo #christendomcollege

text:

text:
i’d like to briefly discuss this because i’ve felt both unable and unsure how to. 
i never reported my assaults. it took me years alone to come to terms with had happened much less tell my family. 
even when i did, reporting was never even a question. both because i knew the odds and more importantly didn’t think i would survive the process of reliving it all through humiliating interrogations by a system trained to blame and dismiss women. 
i’d like to think if my assailant(s) was nominated to the top seat in the nation i’d find the courage to speak up and endure the process, but i honestly don’t know. 
the depression and anxiety i already struggled with were joined by a shattered sense of self-worth and dignity. 
it’s been years of self healing and therapy for me to feel mostly okay with myself most of the time. 
i am so much stronger than the trauma but many days it still floors me. 
watching the news cycle is overwhelming and painful. i am grateful for the sacrifice christine blasey ford has made, but i am enraged and heartbroken she had to. for myself and everyone else who said #metoo , believe women and call your senators.

text:
guys, the last few days have been incredibly powerful and awful for women. 
a stark reminder of my job as a mother to two young sons. for @andre.monet as a father of boys who will become men.
phoenix just randomly picked this book up from our library on his own today. i know he can’t read- but it warmed my heart to see this happen.
we’re going to do our best to raise our sons right. real men don’t hurt women. boys will not be boys, they will be responsible. i hope.

text:
how are there so many parts of me
that never healed up?
how can i claim a name like
arcadia?
•
that’s when life sleeps back in,
and i wonder if i’ll always be
a part of the blackness in the sky
instead of a star.
#wearearcadia
.
.
.
.
.
a lot of women and men have taken the time to share their #whyididntreport story. honestly, it’s not something i’m comfortable with. i don’t think any of us should have to parade around declaring our reasons we didn’t report being sexually assaulted for you to believe us.
point blank: sexual assault isn’t an issue that’s often made up.
i did write a book about a situation that’s eerily similar to #drford and kavanaugh’s experience. it’s honestly an experience that happens so often 90% of the women i know have confided in me about it.

needless to say, this is an issue i’m deeply passionate about.
annoyed with how political my instagram is laterally? the ability to be annoyed by it, instead of pissed and hurt about this situation, is a privilege.
sending love and light to all the survivors out there, who are and aren’t sharing your stories. i hope all of you get a little healing from whatever decision you make.
•
if you want to sign up to receive the book when it’s out, go to the link in my bio, and then go to the #arcadiaorbust mailing list.
it’s a book i think the world truly needs now more than ever. i’d be championing it even harder if i didn’t write it. 💛
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
it's been all i can do to not immerse myself in the news on a regular basis, but this week has been one of the hardest, demoralizing, and retraumatizing. 
right after my worst #metoo experience, one of the very few people that i told responded with: "that's what you get for drinking too much at a party, i guess you learned your lesson." that's why i kept it locked away for years and years and years. not able to move past it or process, holding on to the shame and guilt. 
so here's your gentle reminder that in these trying times, be kind to others, be kind to yourself. you don't know who else is feeling all the feels right now, and please, please, please #believesurvivors.

text:
women— take care of yourself today. heal yourself & your communities despite all the shit going on in this toxic, patriarchal society. know that you are powerful even though people in power are trying to tear you down daily. here’s a poem:
-
i love men
some of my closest friends are men
i love my brothers and my father
-
i have fallen in love with men
-
i love the way they smell 
like bonfires and beer
-
i love the when they hug you
and pick you up a little bit
-
i love how they always have bottle openers on their key chains
-
but i don’t love the world we live in 
where they hurt, abuse and kill women
at alarming rates 
but we are still taught to praise them anyway
- 🖤

text:
blackout

quite a few times this year of the #metoo movement there have been things in my life that threatened to pull me down river in the swift current of distress and overwhelm.  and yet this moment, this moment in our history of unprecedented attack on the feminine by both the patriarchy ( i am distinguishing the patriarchy as different from men who are connected and care about women) and women of the patriarchy who have aligned themselves with the patriarchy in the assault on women, this moment, i am finally galvanized. 
i understand the of the patriarchy and i understand the not wanting to let it go, but it is going, so come with us or not. we will all find our way. 
with most of my abusive sexual and other perpetrators dead or rendered helpless by illness age or disease my world feels possibly safe enough to express myself in. 
i am not going to take myself out again for any reason, not blacken my photo today for any reason. i.am.here. 
i stand for all people to be safe from domestic violence. i am not taking myself out by blackening my photo on fb to say it. i stand strong with and for women and men who are being abused in any way. 
and i stand here fully visible as a light post. i believe my stories and your stories. i know we have been hurt. and, i also know that we don’t have to be washed away or carried out to sea by our past. 
i am stepping in and i am swimming like hell across the current, not fighting against or getting caught in the rip tide of degradation and disregard for women. i am swimming across the current for freedom with a blessing for all of you in my heart. ❤️🔥❤️ men and women who care about dr ford and for all women subjected to violence and degradation but don’t know what to do, share this message, copy and paste this message.  do not disappear today join me by forwarding this together in support of each other, we can change the tide. 
i love us all. this is our future. and above all, be kind ~ katherine

#restoreyourhonor
#brettkavanaugh
#metoo
#itistime  #standupwithme #strongertogether #dontstanddown #dontsitdown #

text:
#whyididntreport 
actually, i did report. i was in grade 12, living without my parents for the first time and realizing how toxic it had been to be around them. my mom had stopped my step dad molesting me when she found out, but we continued to live with him, i was denied access to counselling because he was afraid of consequences. so when i finally had the space at 17 years old to see how hurt i was, i fell apart. i found myself in the office of a school counsellor who was desperately ill equipped to deal with such a real concern. she took me to the hospital, where i was forced to relive my experience to an emergency health worker, who called the police and pressured me to give a statement which would start the legal process against him. in that state of trauma, i gave a statement that didn't accurately reflect the situation because i was so distraught. this compromised my entire case right from the start. a year later, i was called on to give a second statement to support my first account. i came in a more organized headspace, but it was still difficult to recount. and because it didn't match up perfectly with my first account, i got a call saying that i didn't have enough evidence to take the case to crown court, that i would need a support statement from my mom. she had left my abuser by that time, but still fairly recently, and i was nervous how it would turn out. she also lives in an isolated location with no car, so her level of accessibility to give that statement was limited and not well accommodated by the police. so after nearly 3 years of pursuing this case against my abuser, i dropped the charges. because even if my mom was able to give a satisfactory statement to support me, even if it was approved to go to court, it would have taken so much more time and energy away from my own healing, when i was already struggling so deeply to survive the process. being cross examined by a defence lawyer in front of my abuser and a courtroom full of people would have been detrimental to mine and my mother's mental health, would have been a traumatic experience in itself. and i had already endured so much, i was so tired. (cont. in comments.)

text:
our collective stories heal us collectively.
...
i used this line a lot when i launched the project. i didn’t have any evidence to back it up - just a deep and abiding instinct that our collective wound would be healed with our collective truth.
....
the last nine months have been a testament to the power of collective storytelling.... #beautifullstories that healed me in places i didn’t even know i was wounded.
....
it felt appropriate that i would wrap season one of beauti: the interviews this week, making room for season two: the survivor season. if there was ever a week to witness the power of collective storytelling, it was this week.
...
as we move forward in an uncertain world, we can be certain of a few things.
we aren’t going anywhere. we are done shrinking to fit a narrative that doesn’t suit us anymore. and when they take our bodies from us, we’re gonna find a way to take them back.
one #beautifullstory at a time.
....

text:
i practice yoga to remind my body and my brain that i am safe and strong —but this weekend during yoga class a man first grabbed my arm to compliment my tattoo then later grabbed my foot while everyone was laying down with our eyes closed-- when i confronted him and told him not to touch me he tried to brush it off as no big deal and then actually barked at me 🤯 this was all after i had voiced to the class how grateful i was to be healing and feeling stronger again after my pregnancy and csection.  i do a lot of yoga to maintain my peace and equanimity in the face of the worlds challenges and jerky people-- but what the fuck?!? 🤬😓
.
this man had previously told the class how he was fired from his big banking job at wells fargo and was having a terrible week— he then proceeded to hit on my friend within the first 5minutes of class and then grabbed me two separate times. so because a man felt small and defeated in his professional and personal life, he physically imposed himself on me and others—it took the next 20minutes of class to recover and lower my pounding heart rate, calm my erratic breathing, and control my racing thoughts about a man grabbing me while i was vulnerable with my eyes closed during yoga--and now i am left to resolve those feelings of being unsafe and violated with my guard up against men and the world a little bit more today and probably in future yoga classes.
.
this is the consequence of rape culture, a patriarchy that excuses men’s creepy desire to impose themselves on women when it is uninvited and unwelcome. this is trump bragging-about-pussy-grabbing culture. this is sadly american culture. this is a culture of republicans who will betray all women and victims by refusing to even investigate a supreme court judge accused of sexual assault and locking a girl in a room while covering her mouth just so they can go ahead with their political agenda. listening to dr blasey-ford's account of being assaulted by judge kavanaugh was painful and triggering and then my experience this weekend really highlighted how prevalent and ignored sexual harassment and assault are every day.
.
all i can say is #ibelieveher. and #metoo ✊🏽🖤

text:
instead on blacking out my profile, i'm going to share some early paintings i made. i decided to paint something i was afraid of, something that made others uncomfortable (which was the feedback when i exhibited the artwork because these were made well before any massive anti-assault, solidarity movements). they were made in response to "rape watch," which is this concept that women constantly fear being attacked, sexually or otherwise, and i tried to touch on that psychological fear and experience. i'm lucky i've never been assaulted (though i've def. been harassed on many levels). rape watch is why women are taught to walk with our keys between our fingers or to regularly check who's behind us, etc. when walking alone. i hadn't shared these paintings on social media before because even the idea these paintings raised felt shameful, but since then i've done a lot of anti-rape advocacy professionally, my artwork still addresses these topics albeit differently, and quite frankly the times have changed. it is time to share them without shame, and with the hope people start to understand how much the fear of being assaulted is or grappling with the memory of an actual experience or how difficult it is to get people to believe you. 
these paintings were an artistic breakthrough. i was in smfa's post-bac program in 2008 and this was the first time i truly ventured into socially engaged, conceptual art (and they make so much sense with the artwork i do now). nan friedman and ron rizzi were such awesome advocates of these paintings and the growth they showed on my part and to them i am eternally grateful. i still have these paintings. they are massive oil reduction monochromatic paintings, the largest is 12 feet (i was looking at a lot of mark tansey at the time). they are rolled up under my couch, but now it's time they saw the light of day. #believewomen #metoo #blackout #paintings #women #timesup #feministart
name: Katrina Majkut

text:
tw: sexual assault
.
“i didnt know how to tell my mother because she was so in love and i couldn’t imagine being the reason why they got a divorce. so i kept it to myself for 6 years but then i told my sister, and she believed me. then she told our mother, who didn’t believe me. she said he denied it and then she said if it happened it was by accident because he was asleep. 
it has been 30 years and they are still married. .
i only started sharing my truth the last year, and i've learned there was a history of misconduct by him towards female family members. it hurts me that so many have similar stories.
i will speak my truth for others.”
.

text:

#lifeactivated
#lifecaffeinated

text:
self care this weekend has been lots of snuggles with the kitters and puppers, time with the husband and losing myself in homework and books.
the state of our world makes me
angry
sad
furious
rageful 
hurt
myself and so many other women have been forced to relive our trauma of #metoo and #whyididntreport in this past week. i’m grateful for the beautiful community of support and people sharing their stories, their belief #ibelieveyou and standing with one another in hurt and disbelief.
remember to take care of yourself. acknowledge if you’re trauma triggered, find support if you can, unplug from social media and the news if you need, and please feel free to message me if you need a supportive ear. sending out lots of love and light to us all today, and everyday 💕✨

text:
i’m not one to discuss politics and current events like i used to. i’ve mellowed out in recent years for sure and i’m not going to give an opinion on the current case that’s brought up all of this talk, but i will say a few things- 
it took me 5 years to tell anyone in my family i had been assaulted. i still have the messages i sent to my brother. only two friends had known at that point. and now, 5 years after that, i’m publicly saying that it did happen. 
should i have reported it when it happened? probably. but i was scared, ashamed, blamed myself, and aside from that, who would believe me? who would believe that a well respected guy would do such a thing? 
am i going to report it now? no. there’s no proof, it would be my word against his and who would believe that now? 
me, a woman, coming forward a decade after the incident to report it? who could believe that? especially coming from a woman with brain damage who’s memory is already pretty spotty. 
do you see how sad that is? it took 5 years to tell my family and get help from a therapist and it’s taken another 5 years to be able to publicly admit that it even happened and if in another 5 years i get the courage to tell someone who it was...guess what? that doesn’t make it any less true. 
just because a victims healing process is longer than you think it should be, doesn’t mean they aren’t a victim. 
so if you are a person who says that victims shouldn’t wait so long to speak up, or they should’ve “been brave sooner” or insinuates that time passed lessens the validity of the attack, you’re part of the problem and i’ve lost respect and trust for you. you can say “should have, should have” all day long, but until you’ve experienced it, you really have no idea what “should” happen. 
it’s like a knife in the chest to see people who i thought were friends say things that let me know if i came forward with a name, they wouldn’t believe me just because of the amount of time that’s passed. c

to the women who have fabricated rape stories (which is still a small amount compared to actual assaults), please stop. it takes away from those who have truly been assaulted and causes us to fight (cont. in comments)
